<article class="comment comment-by-anonymous odd comment-title-hidden clearfix" about="/comment/23906#comment-23906" typeof="sioc:Post sioct:Comment">
  
      <header class="comment-header">
      <!-- ?php if ($title): ? -->
        <h3 property="dc:title" datatype="" class="comment-title element-invisible"><a href="/comment/23906#comment-23906" rel="bookmark">The solution is to keep your</a></h3>
      <!-- ?php endif; ? -->
          </header>
  
      <footer class="submitted">
            <p class="author-datetime"><span property="dc:date dc:created" content="2014-08-02T08:59:09-05:00" datatype="xsd:dateTime" rel="sioc:has_creator">Submitted by <span class="username" xml:lang="" typeof="sioc:UserAccount" property="foaf:name" datatype="">TMLutas (not verified)</span> on <time datetime="2014-08-02T08:59:09Z" pubdate="pubdate"><span class="date-time">Sat, 2014-08-02 08:59</span></time></span></p>
    </footer>
  
  <div class="comment-content">
    <span rel="sioc:reply_of" resource="/articles/2014/08/Amazon-v-Hatchette-Everyone-Wrong-Me" class="rdf-meta"></span><div class="field field-name-comment-body field-type-text-long field-label-hidden view-mode-full"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="content:encoded"><p>The solution is to keep your powder dry. Monopolies can only extract monopoly profit to the extent they do not exceed the difference between their prices and practices and the next most efficient possible producer. That difference is both in operating the competing business and setting it up in the first place. Keeping that space small will keep Amazon's future monopoly depredations small. It won't stop them. Nothing will stop them from happening. But they're the least cost route to reducing them to a minimum.</p>
</div></div></div>  </div>

  
      <nav class="clearfix"><ul class="links inline"><li class="comment-reply first last"><a href="/comment/reply/3619/23906">reply</a></li></ul></nav>
  
